# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: endangered
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:endangered/adjective] An **adjective** (abbreviated **ADJ**) is a word that describes or defines a noun or noun phrase.
[src:endangered/adjective] Its semantic role is to change information given by the noun.
[src:endangered/adjective] The adjective is considered one of the main parts of speech of the English language, although historically they were classed together with nouns.
[src:endangered/adjective] Nowadays, certain words that usually had been classified as adjectives, including *the*, *this*, *my*, etc., typically are classed separately, as determiners.
[src:endangered/adjective] Depending on the language, an adjective can precede a corresponding noun on a prepositive basis or it can follow a corresponding noun on a postpositive basis.
[src:endangered/adjective] Structural, contextual, and style considerations can impinge on the pre-or post-position of an adjective in a given instance of its occurrence.
[src:endangered/adjective] Adjectives feature as a part of speech (word class) in most languages.
[src:endangered/adjective] In some languages, the words that serve the semantic function of adjectives are categorized together with some other class, such as nouns or verbs.
[src:endangered/adjective] In the phrase *a Ford car*, *Ford* is unquestionably a noun but its function is adjectival (noun adjunct, see below): to modify *car*.
[src:endangered/adjective] In some languages adjectives can function as nouns: for example, the Spanish phrase *un rojo* means 'a red [one]'.
[src:endangered/adjective] This is also possible in English, see above.
[src:endangered/adjective] As for "confusion" with verbs, rather than an adjective meaning "big", a language might have a verb that means "to be big" and could then use an attributive verb construction analogous to "big-being house" to express what in English is called a "big house".
[src:endangered/adjective] Such an analysis is possible for the grammar of Standard Chinese and Korean, for example.
[src:endangered/adjective] Different languages do not use adjectives in exactly the same situations.
[src:endangered/adjective] For example, where English uses *"*to be *hungry*" (*hungry* being an adjective), Dutch, French, and Spanish use "*honger hebben*", "*avoir faim*", and "*tener hambre*" respectively (literally "to have hunger", the words for "hunger" being nouns).
[src:endangered/adjective] Similarly, where Hebrew uses the adjective זקוק‎ (*zaqūq*, roughly "in need of" or "needing"), English uses the verb "to need".
[src:endangered/adjective] In languages that have adjectives as a word class, it is usually an open class; that is, it is relatively common for new adjectives to be formed via such processes as derivation.
[src:endangered/adjective] However, Bantu languages are well known for having only a small closed class of adjectives, and new adjectives are not easily derived.
[src:endangered/adjective] Similarly, native Japanese adjectives (*i*-adjectives) are considered a closed class (as are native verbs), although nouns (an open class) may be used in the genitive to convey some adjectival meanings, and there is also the separate open class of adjectival nouns (*na*-adjectives).
[src:endangered/adjective] Many languages (including English) distinguish between adjectives, which qualify nouns and pronouns, and adverbs, which mainly modify verbs, adjectives, or other adverbs.
[src:endangered/adjective] Not all languages make this exact distinction; many (including English) have words that can function as either.
[src:endangered/adjective] For example, in English, *fast* is an adjective in "a *fast* car" (where it qualifies the noun *car*) but an adverb in "he drove *fast*" (where it modifies the verb *drove*).
[src:endangered/adjective] A German word like *klug* ("clever(ly)") takes endings when used as an attributive adjective but not when used adverbially.
[src:endangered/adjective] Whether these are distinct parts of speech or distinct usages of the same part of speech is a question of analysis.
[src:endangered/adjective] While German linguistic terminology distinguishes *adverbiale* from *adjektivische Formen*, German refers to both as *Eigenschaftswörter* ("property words").
[src:endangered/adjective] Linguists today distinguish determiners from adjectives, considering them to be two separate parts of speech (or *lexical categories*).
[src:endangered/adjective] Determiners formerly were considered to be adjectives in some of their uses.
[src:endangered/adjective] Determiners function neither as nouns nor pronouns but instead characterize a nominal element within a particular context.
[src:endangered/adjective] They generally do this by indicating definiteness (*a* vs.
[src:endangered/adjective] An adjective acts as the head of an *adjective phrase* or *adjectival phrase* (AP).
[src:endangered/adjective] In the simplest case, an adjective phrase consists solely of the adjective; more complex adjective phrases may contain one or more adverbs modifying the adjective ("*very* strong"), or one or more complements (such as "worth *several dollars*", "full *of toys*", or "eager *to please*").
[src:endangered/adjective] In English, attributive adjective phrases that include complements typically follow the noun that they qualify ("an evildoer *devoid of redeeming qualities*").
[src:endangered/adjective] In many languages (including English) it is possible for nouns to modify other nouns.
[src:endangered/adjective] Unlike adjectives, nouns acting as modifiers (called *attributive nouns* or *noun adjuncts*) usually are not predicative; a beautiful park is beautiful, but a car park is not "car".
[src:endangered/adjective] The modifier often indicates origin ("*Virginia* reel"), purpose ("*work* clothes"), semantic patient ("*man* eater") or semantic subject ("*child* actor"); however, it may generally indicate almost any semantic relationship.
[src:endangered/adjective] It is also common for adjectives to be derived from nouns, as in *boyish*, *birdlike*, *behavioral (behavioural)*, *famous*, *manly*, *angelic*, and so on.
[src:endangered/adjective] Many languages have participle forms that can act as noun modifiers either alone or as the head of a phrase.
[src:endangered/adjective] Sometimes participles develop into functional usage as adjectives.
[src:endangered/adjective] Examples in English include *relieved* (the past participle of *relieve*), used as an adjective in passive voice constructs such as "I am so *relieved* to see you".
[src:endangered/adjective] Other examples include *spoken* (the past participle of *speak*) and *going* (the present participle of *go*), which function as attribute adjectives in such phrases as "the *spoken* word" and "the *going* rate".
[src:endangered/adjective] Other constructs that often modify nouns include prepositional phrases (as in "a rebel *without a cause*"), relative clauses (as in "the man *who wasn't there*"), and infinitive phrases (as in "a cake *to die for*").
[src:endangered/adjective] Some nouns can also take complements such as content clauses (as in "the idea *that I would do that*"), but these are not commonly considered modifiers.
[src:endangered/adjective] For more information about possible modifiers and dependents of nouns, see Components of noun phrases.
[src:endangered/adjective] In Australian Aboriginal languages, the distinction between adjectives and nouns is typically thought weak, and many of the languages only use nouns, or nouns with a limited set of adjective-deriving affixes, to modify other nouns.
[src:endangered/adjective] In languages that have a subtle adjective-noun distinction, one way to tell them apart is that a modifying adjective can come to stand in for an entire elided noun phrase, while a modifying noun cannot.
[src:endangered/adjective] For example, in Bardi, the adjective *moorrooloo* 'little' in the phrase *moorrooloo* *baawa* 'little child' can stand on its own to mean 'the little one', while the attributive noun *aamba* 'man' in the phrase *aamba baawa* 'male child' cannot stand for the whole phrase to mean 'the male one'.
[src:endangered/adjective] In other languages, like Warlpiri, nouns and adjectives are lumped together beneath the nominal umbrella because of their shared syntactic distribution as arguments of predicates.
[src:endangered/adjective] The only thing distinguishing them is that some nominals seem to semantically denote entities (typically nouns in English) and some nominals seem to denote attributes (typically adjectives in English).
[src:endangered/adjective] In many languages, attributive adjectives usually occur in a specific order.
[src:endangered/adjective] In general, the adjective order in English can be summarised as: opinion, size, age or shape, colour, origin, material, purpose.
[src:endangered/adjective] Other language authorities, like the *Cambridge Dictionary*, state that shape precedes rather than follows age.
[src:endangered/adjective] Determiners and postdeterminers—articles, numerals, and other limiters (e.g.
[src:endangered/adjective] *three* blind mice)—come before attributive adjectives in English.
[src:endangered/adjective] Although certain combinations of determiners can appear before a noun, they are far more circumscribed than adjectives in their use—typically, only a single determiner would appear before a noun or noun phrase (including any attributive adjectives).
[src:endangered/adjective] Size – adjectives denoting physical size (e.g.
[src:endangered/adjective] Shape or physical quality – adjectives describing more detailed physical attributes than overall size (e.g.
[src:endangered/adjective] Colour – adjectives denoting colour or pattern (e.g.
[src:endangered/adjective] Origin – denominal adjectives denoting source (e.g.
[src:endangered/adjective] This means that, in English, adjectives pertaining to size precede adjectives pertaining to age ("little old", not "old little"), which in turn generally precede adjectives pertaining to colour ("old white", not "white old").
[src:endangered/adjective] This order may be more rigid in some languages than others; in some, like Spanish, it may only be a default (*unmarked*) word order, with other orders being permissible.
[src:endangered/adjective] Other languages, such as Tagalog, follow their adjectival orders as rigidly as English.
[src:endangered/adjective] The normal adjectival order of English may be overridden in certain circumstances, especially when one adjective is being fronted or with ablaut reduplication.
[src:endangered/adjective] For example, the usual order of adjectives in English would result in the phrase "the bad big wolf" (opinion before size), but instead, the usual phrase is "the big bad wolf".
[src:endangered/adjective] Owing partially to borrowings from French, English has some adjectives that follow the noun as postmodifiers, called postpositive adjectives, as in *time immemorial* and *attorney general*.
[src:endangered/adjective] Adjectives may even change meaning depending on whether they precede or follow, as in *proper*: "They live in a *proper town*" (a real town, not a village) vs.
[src:endangered/adjective] "They live in the *town proper* (in the town itself, not in the suburbs).
[src:endangered/adjective] In many languages, some adjectives are *comparable* and the measure of comparison is called *degree*.
[src:endangered/adjective] For example, a person may be "polite", but another person may be "*more* polite", and a third person may be the "*most* polite" of the three.
[src:endangered/adjective] The word "more" here modifies the adjective "polite" to indicate a comparison is being made, and "most" modifies the adjective to indicate an absolute comparison (a *superlative*).
[src:endangered/adjective] Among languages that allow adjectives to be compared, different means are used to indicate comparison.
[src:endangered/adjective] Some languages do not distinguish between comparative and superlative forms.
[src:endangered/adjective] Other languages allow adjectives to be compared but do not have a special comparative form of the adjective.
[src:endangered/adjective] In such cases, as in some Australian Aboriginal languages, case-marking, such as the ablative case, may be used to indicate one entity has more of an adjectival quality than (i.e.
[src:endangered/adjective] Another way to convey comparison is by incorporating the words "more" and "most".
[src:endangered/adjective] There is no simple rule to decide which means is correct for any given adjective, however.
[src:endangered/adjective] The general tendency is for simpler adjectives and those from Anglo-Saxon to take the suffixes, while longer adjectives and those from French, Latin, or Greek do not—but sometimes the *sound* of the word is the deciding factor.
[src:endangered/adjective] Many adjectives do not naturally lend themselves to comparison.
[src:endangered/adjective] For example, some English speakers would argue that it does not make sense to say that one thing is "more ultimate" than another, or that something is "most ultimate", since the word "ultimate" is already absolute in its semantics.
[src:endangered/adjective] Such adjectives are called *non-comparable* or *absolute*.
[src:endangered/adjective] Nevertheless, native speakers will frequently play with the raised forms of adjectives of this sort.
[src:endangered/adjective] Although "pregnant" is logically non-comparable (either one is pregnant or not), one may hear a sentence like "She looks more and more pregnant each day".
[src:endangered/adjective] Comparative and superlative forms are also occasionally used for other purposes than comparison.
[src:endangered/adjective] In Italian, superlatives are frequently used to put strong emphasis on an adjective: *bellissimo* means "most beautiful", but is in fact more commonly heard in the sense "extremely beautiful".
[src:endangered/adjective] Attributive adjectives and other noun modifiers may be used either *restrictively* (helping to identify the noun's referent, hence "restricting" its reference) or *non-restrictively* (helping to describe a noun).
[src:endangered/adjective] Here "difficult" is restrictive – it tells which tasks he avoids, distinguishing these from the easy ones: "Only those tasks that are difficult".
[src:endangered/adjective] In English, restrictiveness is not marked on adjectives but is marked on relative clauses (the difference between "the man *who recognized me* was there" and "the man, *who recognized me*, was there" being one of restrictiveness).
[src:endangered/adjective] In some languages, adjectives alter their form to reflect the gender, case and number of the noun that they describe.
[src:endangered/adjective] Here, a distinction may be made between attributive and predicative usage.
[src:endangered/adjective] In English, adjectives never agree, whereas in French, they always agree.
[src:endangered/adjective] Semanticist Barbara Partee classifies adjectives semantically as intersective, subsective, or nonsubsective, with nonsubsective adjectives being plain nonsubsective or privative.
[src:endangered/endangered-species] An **endangered species** is a species that is very likely to become extinct in the near future, either worldwide or in a particular region.
[src:endangered/endangered-species] Endangered species may be at risk due to factors such as habitat loss, poaching, invasive species, and climate change.
[src:endangered/endangered-species] The International Union for Conservation of Nature (IUCN) Red List lists the global conservation status of many species, and various other agencies assess the status of species within particular areas.
[src:endangered/endangered-species] Many nations have laws that protect conservation-reliant species which, for example, forbid hunting or harvesting, restrict land development, or create protected areas.
[src:endangered/endangered-species] Some endangered species are the target of extensive conservation efforts such as captive breeding and habitat restoration.
[src:endangered/endangered-species] Human activity is a significant factor in causing species to become endangered.
[src:endangered/endangered-species] The conservation status of a species indicates the likelihood that it will become extinct.
[src:endangered/endangered-species] Multiple factors are considered when assessing the status of a species; e.g., such statistics as the number remaining, the overall increase or decrease in the population over time, breeding success rates, or known threats.
[src:endangered/endangered-species] The IUCN Red List of Threatened Species is the best-known worldwide conservation status listing and ranking system.
[src:endangered/endangered-species] The IUCN Red List of Threatened Species by the International Union for Conservation of Nature is the best known worldwide conservation status listing and ranking system.
[src:endangered/endangered-species] Species are classified by the IUCN Red List into nine groups set through criteria such as rate of decline, population size, area of geographic distribution, and degree of population and distribution fragmentation.
[src:endangered/endangered-species] Also included are species that have gone extinct since 1500 CE.
[src:endangered/endangered-species] When discussing the IUCN Red List, the official term "threatened" is a grouping of three categories: critically endangered, endangered, and vulnerable.
[src:endangered/endangered-species] Over 50% of the world's species are estimated to be at risk of extinction, but the frontiers between categories such as "endangered", "rare", or "locally extinct" species are often difficult to draw given the general paucity of data on most of these species.
[src:endangered/endangered-species] This is notably the case in the world's oceans, where distances are vast and endangered species not seen for decades may go extinct unnoticed.
[src:endangered/endangered-species] Internationally, 195 countries have signed an accord to create Biodiversity Action Plans that will protect endangered and other threatened species.
[src:endangered/endangered-species] In the United States, such plans are usually called Species Recovery Plans.
[src:endangered/endangered-species] The species under the index include: mammals, birds, amphibians, cycads, and corals.
[src:endangered/endangered-species] Those species of "Near Threatened" (NT) and "Least Concern" (LC) status have been assessed and found to have relatively robust and healthy populations, though these may be in decline.
[src:endangered/endangered-species] Unlike their more general use elsewhere, the List uses the terms "endangered species" and "threatened species" with particular meanings: "Endangered" (EN) species lie between "Vulnerable" (VU) and "Critically Endangered" (CR) species.
[src:endangered/endangered-species] In 2012, the IUCN Red List listed 3,079 animal and 2,655 plant species as endangered (EN) worldwide.
[src:endangered/endangered-species] Brazil is one of the most biodiverse countries in the world, if not the most.
[src:endangered/endangered-species] It houses not only the Amazon forest but the Atlantic forest, the savanna-like Cerrado among other biomes.
[src:endangered/endangered-species] Due to the high density of some of its well-preserved rainforests, wildlife trafficking, which along with deforestation is one of the biggest endangerment drivers in Brazil, has become a challenge.
[src:endangered/endangered-species] Though such agencies can collect their data, each system operates relatively on its own when it comes to wildlife trafficking.
[src:endangered/endangered-species] However, both the agencies and the NGO's working in Brazil agree that the birds account for about 80% of trafficked species in the country.
[src:endangered/endangered-species] Additionally, some environment experts and scientists point to the disbanding of environment agencies and the repeal of laws in Brazil under the presidency of Jair Bolsonaro as one of the reasons behind a surge in the number of endangered species.
[src:endangered/endangered-species] In one occasion during his presidency some fines totaling US$6.7 billion on environment criminals were revoked and at least one fine (related to illegal fishing) imposed on Bolsonaro himself was cancelled and the agent who fined him was demoted.
[src:endangered/endangered-species] In the past, Brazil has successfully saved the endemic golden lion tamarin from extinction.
[src:endangered/endangered-species] Massive campaigns to raise awareness among people by NGO's and governments, which included printing depictions of the golden lion tamarin in the 20 reais Brazilian banknotes (still in circulation), are credited with getting the species out of the critically endangered animals list.
[src:endangered/endangered-species] There is data from the United States that shows a correlation between human populations and threatened and endangered species.
[src:endangered/endangered-species] Using species data from the Database on the Economics and Management of Endangered Species database and the period that the Endangered Species Act (ESA) has been in existence, 1970 to 1997, a table was created that suggests a positive relationship between human activity and species endangerment.
[src:endangered/endangered-species] Carbon dioxide in Earth's atmosphere is asserted to be one of the leading causes of animal endangerment.
[src:endangered/endangered-species] Under the Endangered Species Act of 1973 in the United States, species may be listed as "endangered" or "threatened".
[src:endangered/endangered-species] The Salt Creek tiger beetle is an example of an endangered subspecies protected under the ESA.
[src:endangered/endangered-species] The US Fish and Wildlife Service, as well as the National Marine Fisheries Service are held responsible for classifying and protecting endangered species.
[src:endangered/endangered-species] They are also responsible for adding a particular species to the list, which can be a long, controversial process.
[src:endangered/endangered-species] The act adds numerous other provisions as well, including the designation of endangered species' critical habitats and a requirement to develop a recovery plan for the species.
[src:endangered/endangered-species] On top of this, the ESA protects endangered species from government policies; for instance, federal agencies must consult the Fish and Wildlife Service or the National Marine Fisheries Service before executing any action that may jeopardize threatened species or their habitats.
[src:endangered/endangered-species] Some endangered species laws are controversial.
[src:endangered/endangered-species] Typical areas of controversy include criteria for placing a species on the endangered species list and rules for removing a species from the list once its population has recovered.
[src:endangered/endangered-species] Whether restrictions on land development constitute a "taking" of land by the government; the related question of whether private landowners should be compensated for the loss of uses of their areas; and obtaining reasonable exceptions to protection laws.
[src:endangered/endangered-species] Also lobbying from hunters and various industries like the petroleum industry, construction industry, and logging, has been an obstacle in establishing endangered species laws.
[src:endangered/endangered-species] The Bush administration lifted a policy that required federal officials to consult a wildlife expert before taking actions that could damage endangered species.
[src:endangered/endangered-species] Under the Obama administration, this policy was reinstated.
[src:endangered/endangered-species] Being listed as an endangered species can have an indirect negative effect since the perceived increase in rarity could make a species more desirable for collectors and poachers.
[src:endangered/endangered-species] This effect is potentially reducible, such as in China where commercially farmed turtles may be reducing some of the pressure to poach endangered species.
[src:endangered/endangered-species] Another problem with the listing of species is its effect of inciting the use of the "shoot, shovel, and shut-up" method of clearing endangered species from an area of land.
[src:endangered/endangered-species] Some landowners currently may perceive a diminution in value for their land after finding an endangered animal on it.
[src:endangered/endangered-species] They have allegedly opted to kill and bury the animals or destroy habitat silently.
[src:endangered/endangered-species] Thus removing the problem from their land, but at the same time further reducing the population of an endangered species.
[src:endangered/endangered-species] The effectiveness of the ESA– which coined the term "endangered species"– has been questioned by business advocacy groups and their publications but is nevertheless widely recognized by wildlife scientists who work with the species as an effective recovery tool.
[src:endangered/endangered-species] Nineteen species have been delisted and recovered and 93% of listed species in the north eastern United States have a recovering or stable population.
[src:endangered/endangered-species] Currently, 1,556 endangered species are under protection by government law.
[src:endangered/endangered-species] This approximation, however, does not take into consideration the species threatened with endangerment that are not included under the protection of laws like the Endangered Species Act.
[src:endangered/endangered-species] According to NatureServe's global conservation status, approximately thirteen percent of vertebrates (excluding marine fish), seventeen percent of vascular plants, and six to eighteen percent of fungi are considered imperiled.
[src:endangered/endangered-species] Thus, in total, between seven and eighteen percent of the United States' known animals, fungi and plants are near extinction.
[src:endangered/endangered-species] This total is substantially more than the number of species protected in the United States under the Endangered Species Act.
[src:endangered/endangered-species] Ever since humankind began hunting to preserve itself, over-hunting and fishing have been a large and dangerous problem.
[src:endangered/endangered-species] Many began as food sources seen as necessary for survival but became the target of sport.
[src:endangered/endangered-species] However, due to major efforts to prevent extinction, the bald eagle, or *Haliaeetus leucocephalus* is now under the category of Least Concern on the red list.
[src:endangered/endangered-species] A present-day example of the over-hunting of a species can be seen in the oceans as populations of certain whales have been greatly reduced.
[src:endangered/endangered-species] Large whales like the blue whale, bowhead whale, finback whale, gray whale, sperm whale, and humpback whale are some of the eight whales which are currently still included on the Endangered Species List.
[src:endangered/endangered-species] Actions have been taken to attempt a reduction in whaling and increase population sizes.
[src:endangered/endangered-species] The actions include prohibiting all whaling in United States waters, the formation of the CITES treaty which protects all whales, along with the formation of the International Whaling Commission (IWC).
[src:endangered/endangered-species] But even though all of these movements have been put in place, countries such as Japan continue to hunt and harvest whales under the claim of "scientific purposes".
[src:endangered/endangered-species] Over-hunting, climatic change and habitat loss leads in landing species in endangered species list.
[src:endangered/endangered-species] It could mean that extinction rates could increase to a large extent in the future.
[src:endangered/endangered-species] Endangered species are addressed through Canada's Species at Risk Act.
[src:endangered/endangered-species] A species is deemed threatened or endangered when it is on the verge of extinction or extirpation.
[src:endangered/endangered-species] Once a species is deemed threatened or endangered, the Act requires that a recovery plan to be developed that indicates how to stop or reverse the species' population decline.
[src:endangered/endangered-species] As of 2024, there are 339 Canadian species classified as endangered by the IUCN Red List.
[src:endangered/endangered-species] The World Wide Fund-India raises concern in the longevity of the following animal species: the Red Panda, the Bengal Tiger, the Ganges River Dolphin, the Asian Elephant.
[src:endangered/endangered-species] India has had significantly high rates of poaching and animal trafficking, threatening many animal species there.
[src:endangered/endangered-species] Since 1987, over half of trafficked tiger seizures have been within India.
[src:endangered/endangered-species] The government signed the Wildlife Protection Act and also joined the Convention on the International Trade in 1976, to prevent poaching from harming its wildlife.
[src:endangered/endangered-species] The introduction of non-indigenous species to an area can disrupt the ecosystem to such an extent that native species become endangered.
[src:endangered/endangered-species] Such introductions may be termed introduced or invasive species.
[src:endangered/endangered-species] In some cases, the invasive species compete with the native species for food or prey on the natives.
[src:endangered/endangered-species] In other cases, a stable ecological balance may be upset by predation or other causes leading to unexpected species decline.
[src:endangered/endangered-species] New species may also carry diseases to which the native species have no exposure or resistance.
[src:endangered/endangered-species] The continent of Oceania is under much more pressure, as the invasive birds and mammals there have no natural predators.
[src:endangered/endangered-species] Notably, the threat posed by introduces species may be greater than anticipated due to the threats on endangered species that have not yet had a significant effect, but likely will in the future.
[src:endangered/endangered-species] The World Wildlife Fund (WWF) emphasizes that our planet is warming at a rate faster than any time in the past 10,000 years, necessitating species to adapt to new climate patterns, such as variations in rainfall and longer, warmer summers.
[src:endangered/endangered-species] Fish & Wildlife Service highlighted efforts to understand and mitigate the impact of climate change on species through scientific research, modeling, and conservation actions.
[src:endangered/endangered-species] This includes evaluating the current condition of species, their genetic variation, and how changes in their environment may affect their survival.
[src:endangered/endangered-species] The International Union for Conservation of Nature (IUCN) reports that the approximately 1 °C rise in mean global temperature due to human activities is causing serious impacts on species, including changes in abundance, genetic composition, behavior, and survival.
[src:endangered/endangered-species] The IUCN stresses the importance of environmental policies aimed at reducing CO 2 emissions to lessen the impact of climate change on species.
[src:endangered/endangered-species] Tools like the IUCN Red List and guidelines for assessing species' vulnerability to climate change are vital for conservation efforts.
[src:endangered/endangered-species] In addition, climate change can lead to species decreasing in areas where they once thrived, by being forced to migrate or even going extinct from inhospitable conditions, invasive species, and fragmentation.
[src:endangered/endangered-species] A study cited by WWF found that one in six species is at risk of extinction due to climate change if no action is taken.
[src:endangered/endangered-species] The phenomenon of species shifting their ranges in response to changing climates, finding new or shrinking habitats, illustrates the direct impact of global warming on biodiversity.
[src:endangered/endangered-species] Another major concern is rising ocean acidity caused from excess CO2 in the atmosphere.
[src:endangered/endangered-species] For example, the Emperor Penguins, which rely on Antarctic sea ice for breeding, shelter, and food, are directly threatened by the melting of ice sheets.
[src:endangered/endangered-species] Similarly, the Mount Rainier white-tailed ptarmigan, adapted to alpine mountaintops, faces habitat loss due to climate changes in snowfall patterns and rising temperatures.
[src:endangered/endangered-species] Another example is in the case of the Salton Sea in California.
[src:endangered/endangered-species] This area is a critical habitat for many endangered and watched species, as well as many migratory birds.
[src:endangered/endangered-species] Due to environmental shifts from climate change and the addition of agriculture in the surrounding plains, the system has become almost irreparably damaged.
[src:endangered/endangered-species] The warming temperatures has caused mass evaporation, leaving the Sea much more saline and with much more exposed playa.
[src:endangered/endangered-species] This not only damages air quality but also has caused fish kills to accumulate as shown pictured below.
[src:endangered/endangered-species] Captive breeding is the process of breeding rare or endangered species in human controlled environments with restricted settings, such as wildlife reserves, zoos, and other conservation facilities.
[src:endangered/endangered-species] Captive breeding is meant to save species from extinction and so stabilise the population of the species that it will not disappear.
[src:endangered/endangered-species] This technique has worked for many species for some time, with probably the oldest known such instances of captive mating being attributed to menageries of European and Asian rulers, an example being the Père David's deer.
[src:endangered/endangered-species] However, captive breeding techniques are usually difficult to implement for such highly mobile species as some migratory birds (e.g. cranes) and fishes (e.g. hilsa).
[src:endangered/endangered-species] Additionally, if the captive breeding population is too small, then inbreeding may occur due to a reduced gene pool and reduce resistance.
[src:endangered/endangered-species] In 1981, the Association of Zoos and Aquariums (AZA) created a Species Survival Plan (SSP) to help preserve specific endangered and threatened species through captive breeding.
[src:endangered/endangered-species] With over 450 SSP Plans, some endangered species are covered by the AZA with plans to cover population management goals and recommendations for breeding for a diverse and healthy population, created by Taxon Advisory Groups.
[src:endangered/endangered-species] These programs are commonly created as a last resort effort.
[src:endangered/endangered-species] SSP Programs regularly participate in species recovery, veterinary care for wildlife disease outbreaks, and some other wildlife conservation efforts.
[src:endangered/endangered-species] The AZA's Species Survival Plan also has breeding and transfer programs, both within and outside of AZA – certified zoos and aquariums.
[src:endangered/endangered-species] Some animals that are part of SSP programs are giant pandas, lowland gorillas, and California condors.
[src:endangered/endangered-species] Whereas poaching substantially reduces endangered animal populations, legal, for-profit, private farming does the opposite.
[src:endangered/endangered-species] It has substantially increased the populations of the southern black rhinoceros and southern white rhinoceros.
[src:endangered/endangered-species] Richard Emslie, a scientific officer at the IUCN, said of such programs, "Effective law enforcement has become much easier now that the animals are largely privately owned...
[src:endangered/endangered-species] We have been able to bring local communities into conservation programs.
[src:endangered/endangered-species] There are increasingly strong economic incentives attached to looking after rhinos rather than simply poaching: from Eco-tourism or selling them on for a profit.
[src:endangered/endangered-species] Conservation experts view the effect of China's turtle farming on the wild turtle populations of China and South-Eastern Asia– many of which are endangered– as "poorly understood".
[src:endangered/endangered-species] The conservation expert Peter Paul van Dijk noted that turtle farmers often believe that animals caught wild are superior breeding stock.
[src:endangered/endangered-species] Turtle farmers may, therefore, seek and catch the last remaining wild specimens of some endangered turtle species.
[src:endangered/endangered-species] In 2015, researchers in Australia managed to coax southern bluefin tuna to breed in landlocked tanks, raising the possibility that fish farming may be able to save the species from overfishing.
[src:endangered/endangered-species] Some scientists have proposed that redefining the baseline for assessing recovery of an endangered species may be necessary as a last resort in the face of extinction, as the increased flexibility provides more realistic recovery goals in the face of extinction.
[src:endangered/endangered-species] This strategy, however, needs to be pursued with significant care and is typically not considered before attempting recovery within the natural range when possible, due to carrying additional risks and potential unintended consequences.
[src:endangered/endangered-species] These changes can come in many forms, including relocating a species to a new and better suited habitat, allowing the species to breed with other similar species, or accepting that the modern stable population may be less than it was in the past.
[src:endangered/endangered-species] An example of these strategies being put into action is through the Florida panther.
[src:endangered/endangered-species] To save the species, cougars from Texas were introduced, turning a large subset of the panther population into panther–cougar hybrids that were well suited to the environment, facilitating the recovery of the population.
[src:endangered/endangered-species] Hawaiian monk seals are one of the most endangered seal species in the world.
[src:endangered/endangered-species] Conservation initiatives have focused on mitigating human-seal conflicts, rehabilitating injured seals, and extensive monitoring to ensure their survival.
[src:endangered/endangered-species] These efforts have led to a gradual increase in their population.
[src:endangered/endangered-species] Once on the brink of extinction in the contiguous United States with only 417 known nesting pairs in 1963 due to pesticide use and habitat destruction, the bald eagle population has made a remarkable recovery.
[src:endangered/endangered-species] By 2020, the number of nesting pairs had surged to 71,400.
[src:endangered/endangered-species] Major strategies employed to help raise populations included the provision of eaglets from stable regions to more threatened regions, and major land purchases to act as sanctuaries for the eagles.
[src:endangered/endangered-species] Thanks to habitat protection, legal protection, and DDT ban efforts, the bald eagle was removed from the list of threatened and endangered species.
[src:endangered/endangered-species] Starting in 1995 and 1996, 31 gray wolves from western Canada were relocated to Yellowstone, where they were temporarily kept in acclimation pens before being released into the wild.
[src:endangered/endangered-species] This careful reintroduction aimed to restore a key predator to the ecosystem, which had profound effects on the park's wildlife dynamics.
[src:endangered/endangered-species] After being nearly eradicated in the lower 48 states by the early 20th century, reintroduction and protective measures have allowed their populations to rebound significantly.
[src:endangered/endangered-species] By 2017, gray wolves were delisted in Montana, Idaho, and Wyoming, indicating a recovery to a point where they were no longer considered endangered in these areas.
[src:endangered/endangered-species] Beginning in 1999, the Channel Islands National Park launched an ambitious recovery program for the island fox, incorporating several strategies: captive breeding and reintroduction, removal of predatory golden eagles, re-establishment of bald eagles, and eradication of non-native ungulates.
[src:endangered/endangered-species] Department of the Interior officially recognized the recovery as the fastest for any Endangered Species Act-listed mammal in the U.S., announcing the delisting of three island fox subspecies in 2016.
[src:endangered/endangered-species] This recovery, from near extinction in the late 1990s to robust populations by the mid-2010s, underscores the power of partnership-driven conservation.
[src:endangered/endangered-species] The Purple Emperor, native to the UK, has seen a significant comeback in recent years, expanding from southern England to a large portion of the British Isles.
[src:endangered/endangered-species] Conservation groups have aided this process through the planting of goat willows in many forests, an important food source for the butterfly larvae.
[src:endangered/endangered-species] The territorial nature of the species makes this process more complicated, requiring many willow trees be planted over a large area, but groups such as Butterfly Conservation have made the recovery process possible.
[src:endangered/noun] In grammar, a **noun** is a word that represents a concrete or abstract thing, like living creatures, places, actions, events, qualities, states of existence, and ideas.
[src:endangered/noun] To summarize this, nouns signify an object or idea.
[src:endangered/noun] A noun may serve as an object or subject within a phrase, clause, or sentence.
[src:endangered/noun] In linguistics, nouns constitute a lexical category (part of speech) defined according to how its members combine with members of other lexical categories.
[src:endangered/noun] The syntactic occurrence of nouns differs among languages.
[src:endangered/noun] In English, prototypical nouns are common nouns or proper nouns that can occur with determiners, articles and attributive adjectives, and can function as the head of a noun phrase.
[src:endangered/noun] According to traditional and popular classification, pronouns are distinct from nouns, but in much modern theory they are considered a subclass of nouns.
[src:endangered/noun] Every language has various linguistic and grammatical distinctions between nouns and verbs.
[src:endangered/noun] Word classes (parts of speech) were described by Sanskrit grammarians from at least the 5th century BC.
[src:endangered/noun] In Yāska's *Nirukta*, the noun (*nāma*) is one of the four main categories of words defined.
[src:endangered/noun] The Ancient Greek equivalent was *ónoma* (ὄνομα), referred to by Plato in the *Cratylus*, and later listed as one of the eight parts of speech in *The Art of Grammar*, attributed to Dionysius Thrax (2nd century BC).
[src:endangered/noun] The term used in Latin grammar was *nōmen*.
[src:endangered/noun] All of these terms for "noun" were also words meaning "name".
[src:endangered/noun] The English word *noun* is derived from the Latin term, through the Anglo-Norman *nom* (other forms include *nomme*, and *noun* itself).
[src:endangered/noun] The word classes were defined partly by the grammatical forms that they take.
[src:endangered/noun] In Sanskrit, Greek, and Latin, for example, nouns are categorized by gender and inflected for case and number.
[src:endangered/noun] Because adjectives share these three grammatical categories, adjectives typically were placed in the same class as nouns.
[src:endangered/noun] Similarly, the Latin term *nōmen* includes both nouns (substantives) and adjectives, as originally did the English word *noun*, the two types being distinguished as *nouns substantive* and *nouns adjective* (or *substantive nouns* and *adjective nouns*, or simply *substantives* and *adjectives*).
[src:endangered/noun] Many European languages use a cognate of the word *substantive* as the basic term for *noun* (for example, Spanish *sustantivo*, "noun").
[src:endangered/noun] Nouns in the dictionaries of such languages are demarked by the abbreviation *s.* or *sb.* instead of *n.*, which may be used for proper nouns or neuter nouns instead.
[src:endangered/noun] In English, some modern authors use the word *substantive* to refer to a class that includes both nouns (single words) and noun phrases (multiword units that are sometimes called *noun equivalents*).
[src:endangered/noun] It can also be used as a counterpart to *attributive* when distinguishing between a noun being used as the head (main word) of a noun phrase and a noun being used as a noun adjunct.
[src:endangered/noun] For example, the noun *knee* can be said to be used substantively in *my knee hurts*, but attributively in *the patient needed knee replacement*.
[src:endangered/noun] A noun can co-occur with an article or an attributive adjective.
[src:endangered/noun] In the following, an asterisk (*) in front of an example means that this example is ungrammatical.
[src:endangered/noun] Nouns have sometimes been characterized in terms of the grammatical categories by which they may be varied (for example gender, case, and number).
[src:endangered/noun] Such definitions tend to be language-specific, since different languages may apply different categories.
[src:endangered/noun] Nouns are frequently defined, particularly in informal contexts, in terms of their semantic properties (their meanings).
[src:endangered/noun] Nouns are described as words that refer to a *person*, *place*, *thing*, *event*, *substance*, *quality*, *quantity*, etc., but this manner of definition has been criticized as uninformative.
[src:endangered/noun] Several English nouns lack an intrinsic referent of their own: *behalf* (as in *on behalf of*), *dint* (*by dint of*), and *sake* (*for the sake of*).
[src:endangered/noun] Moreover, other parts of speech may have reference-like properties: the verbs *to rain* or *to mother*, or adjectives like *red*; and there is little difference between the adverb *gleefully* and the prepositional phrase *with glee*.
[src:endangered/noun] A functional approach defines a noun as a word that can be the head of a nominal phrase, i.e., a phrase with referential function, without needing to go through morphological transformation.
[src:endangered/noun] Nouns can have a number of different properties and are often sub-categorized based on various of these criteria, depending on their occurrence in a language.
[src:endangered/noun] Nouns may be classified according to morphological properties such as which prefixes or suffixes they take, and also their relations in syntax – how they combine with other words and expressions of various types.
[src:endangered/noun] Many such classifications are language-specific, given the obvious differences in syntax and morphology.
[src:endangered/noun] In English for example, it might be noted that nouns are words that can co-occur with definite articles (as stated at the start of this article), but this could not apply in Russian, which has no definite articles.
[src:endangered/noun] In some languages common and proper nouns have grammatical gender, typically masculine, feminine, and neuter.
[src:endangered/noun] The gender of a noun (as well as its number and case, where applicable) will often require agreement in words that modify or are used along with it.
[src:endangered/noun] In French for example, the singular form of the definite article is *le* for masculine nouns and *la* for feminine; adjectives and certain verb forms also change (sometimes with the simple addition of *-e* for feminine).
[src:endangered/noun] Grammatical gender often correlates with the form of the noun and the inflection pattern it follows; for example, in both Italian and Romanian most nouns ending in *-a* are feminine.
[src:endangered/noun] Gender can also correlate with the sex or social gender of the noun's referent, particularly in the case of nouns denoting people (and sometimes animals), though with exceptions (the feminine French noun *personne* can refer to a male or a female person).
[src:endangered/noun] In Modern English, even common nouns like *hen* and *princess* and proper nouns like *Alicia* do not have grammatical gender (their femininity has no relevance in syntax), though they denote persons or animals of a specific sex.
[src:endangered/noun] The gender of a pronoun must be appropriate for the item referred to: "The *girl* said the *ring* was from *her* new *boyfriend*, but *he* denied *it* was from *him*" (three nouns; and three gendered pronouns: or four, if this *her* is counted as a possessive pronoun).
[src:endangered/noun] Many nouns have both countable and uncountable uses; for example, *soda* is countable in "give me three sodas", but uncountable in "he likes soda".
[src:endangered/noun] Some nouns have both concrete and abstract meanings: *art* usually refers to something abstract ("Art is important in human culture"), but it can also refer to a concrete item ("I put my daughter's art up on the fridge").
[src:endangered/noun] A noun might have a literal (concrete) and also a figurative (abstract) meaning: "a brass *key*" and "the *key* to success"; "a *block* in the pipe" and "a mental *block*".
[src:endangered/noun] Similarly, some abstract nouns have developed etymologically by figurative extension from literal roots (*drawback*, *fraction*, *holdout*, *uptake*).
[src:endangered/noun] Many abstract nouns in English are formed by adding a suffix (*-ness*, *-ity*, *-ion*) to adjectives or verbs (*happiness* and *serenity* from the adjectives *happy* and *serene*; *circulation* from the verb *circulate*).
[src:endangered/noun] Illustrating the wide range of possible classifying principles for nouns, the Awa language of Papua New Guinea regiments nouns according to how *ownership* is assigned: as alienable possession or inalienable possession.
[src:endangered/noun] An alienably possessed item (a tree, for example) can exist even without a possessor.
[src:endangered/noun] But inalienably possessed items are necessarily associated with their possessor and are referred to differently, for example with nouns that function as kin terms (meaning "father", etc.), body-part nouns (meaning "shadow", "hair", etc.), or part–whole nouns (meaning "top", "bottom", etc.).
[src:endangered/noun] A noun phrase (or **NP**) is a phrase usually headed by a common noun, a proper noun, or a pronoun.
[src:endangered/noun] The head may be the only constituent, or it may be modified by determiners and adjectives.
[src:endangered/noun] For example, "The dog sat near Ms Curtis and wagged its tail" contains three NPs: *the dog* (subject of the verbs *sat* and *wagged*); *Ms Curtis* (complement of the preposition *near*); and *its tail* (object of *wagged*).
[src:endangered/noun] "You became their teacher" contains two NPs: *you* (subject of *became*); and *their teacher*.
[src:endangered/noun] For example, in the sentence "Gareth thought she was weird", the word *she* is a pronoun that refers to a person just as the noun *Gareth* does.
[src:endangered/noun] The word *one* can replace parts of noun phrases, and it sometimes stands in for a noun.
[src:endangered/noun] But *one* can also stand in for larger parts of a noun phrase.
[src:endangered/noun] For example, in the following example, *one* can stand in for *new car*.
[src:endangered/noun] Nominalization is a process whereby a word that belongs to another part of speech comes to be used as a noun.
[src:endangered/noun] This can be a way to create new nouns, or to use other words in ways that resemble nouns.
[src:endangered/noun] In French and Spanish, for example, adjectives frequently act as nouns referring to people who have the characteristics denoted by the adjective.
[src:endangered/noun] is a worldwide association of political parties.
